{{for|the battle itself|Battle of Princeton}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file = The Death of General Mercer at the Battle of Princeton January 3 1777.jpeg | image_size = | title = The Death of General Mercer at the Battle of Princeton, January 3, 1777 | artist = [[John Trumbull]] | year = {{circa|1787}}–{{circa|1831}} | medium = [[oil on canvas]] | height_metric = 51.1 | width_metric = 75.9 | height_imperial = 20.125 | width_imperial = 29.875 | city = [[New Haven, Connecticut]] | museum = [[Yale University Art Gallery]] }}
'''''The Death of General Mercer at the Battle of Princeton, January 3, 1777''''' is the title of an [[oil painting]] by the American artist [[John Trumbull]] depicting the death of the American General [[Hugh Mercer]] at the [[Battle of Princeton]] on January 3, 1777 during the [[American Revolutionary War]]. The painting was Trumbull’s first depiction of an American victory.<ref name=yale>{{cite book|last1=Cooper|first1=Helen A.|title=Life, Liberty, and the Pursuit of Happiness: American Art from the Yale University Art Gallery |date=2008|publisher=[[Yale University Art Gallery]]|isbn=978-0-300-12289-3|pages=90–91|location=New Haven, Conn.}}</ref> It is one of a series of [[historical painting]]s on the war, which also includes the ''[[Declaration of Independence (Trumbull)|Declaration of Independence]]'' and ''[[The Capture of the Hessians at Trenton, December 26, 1776]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artgallery.yale.edu/collections/objects/90|title=The Capture of the Hessians at Trenton, December 26, 1776|publisher=[[Yale University Art Gallery]]}}</ref>
The artist expressed his great admiration for General [[George Washington]] in this painting as he wrote in the catalogue for his exhibited works at [[Yale University]] in 1835:{{quote| Thus, in the short space of nine days, an extensive country, an entire State, was wrested from the hands of a victorious enemy, superior in numbers, in arms and in discipline, by the wisdom, activity and energy of one great mind.<ref name=trumbull>{{cite book|last1=Trumbull|first1=John|author-link=John Trumbull|title=Catalogue of Paintings, by Colonel Trumbull; Including Eight Subjects of the American Revolution, with Near Two Hundred and Fifty Portraits of Persons Distinguished in That Important Period. Painted by Him from the Life.|date=1835|publisher=Gallery of Yale College|pages=19–22|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ShtGAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA19}}</ref>}}
It was a personal favorite of Trumbull himself. When asked by [[Benjamin Silliman]] which paintings he would save from destruction in the Trumbull Gallery at Yale, he said this one.<ref name=yale/><ref name=artstor/>
Trumbull used the General's son, Hugh Jr., as a model for the painting.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hugh Mercer, Jr. (Study for "The Death of General Mercer at the Battle of Princeton, January 3, 1777")|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/collection/the-collection-online/search/12821|publisher=[[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]]}}</ref>
==Description== The picture displays several different events of the battle as if they occurred simultaneously.<ref name=yale/><ref name=artstor>{{cite web|title=The Death of General Mercer at the Battle of Princeton, January 3, 1777 (Descriptive data)|url=http://search.openlibrary.artstor.org/object/AYALEARTIG_10312577019|publisher=Yale University Art Gallery}}</ref>
At the center, American General [[Hugh Mercer]], with his dead horse beneath him, is shown mortally wounded. Mercer was commanding the leading division of the [[Continental Army]] when attacked by British Colonel [[Charles Mawhood]] near [[Princeton, New Jersey]]. Mercer's horse was killed and he was attacked by two [[grenadiers]]. The British were in control of the battle at this moment.<ref name=trumbull/> Mercer would be treated for his wounds by Dr. [[Benjamin Rush]] the next day, January 4, but died on January 12 as a result, Dr. Rush believed, of a concussion caused by a musket butt to the head<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rush|first1=Benjamin|author-link1=Benjamin Rush|title=A Memorial containing Travels Through Life or Sundry Incidents in the Life of Dr. Benjamin Rush|date=1905|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=abZOAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA97|pages=97–98}}</ref>
At the left, American Daniel Neil{{efn|misidentified by art historians as American Lieutenant Charles Turnbull<ref name=fischer/>}} is shown bayoneted against a cannon.<ref name=yale/>
At the right, British Captain [[William Leslie (British Army officer)|William Leslie]] is shown mortally wounded. Leslie died during the battle and was put on a wagon by the British that was later taken by the Americans. Rush also learned of his death on January 4. He would be buried at [[Pluckemin, New Jersey]] the next day, January 5.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hawke|first=David Freeman|title=Benjamin Rush: Revolutionary Gadfly|year=1971|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z1u9-0UX1E4C&pg=PA180|page=180}}</ref>
In the background, American General [[George Washington]] and Dr. Benjamin Rush enter the scene. After Mercer became a casualty, Washington needed to lead the charge to overtake Mawhood's troops and win the battle.<ref name=fischer>{{cite book|last1=Fischer|first1=David Hackett|authorlink=David Hackett Fischer|title=Washington's Crossing|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Oreq1YztDcQC&pg=PA333&lpg=PA333|location=New York|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=2006|isbn=0-19-517034-2|pages=333–338}}</ref> On the far left, American General [[Thomas Mifflin]] is shown leading a cavalry charge.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Caldwell|first1=John|last2=Rodriguez Roque|first2=Oswaldo|title=American Paintings in The Metropolitan Museum of Art|volume=1|date=1994|publisher=[[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]]|pages=214–215|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dYdWBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA214|chapter=Thomas Mifflin}}</ref> American Colonel [[John Cadwalader (general)|John Cadwalader]] and British Colonel Edmund Eyre are also depicted.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Franklin Bowditch|last1=Dexter|author-link1=Franklin Bowditch Dexter|title=A Catalogue, with Descriptive Notices, of the Portraits, Busts, etc. Belonging to Yale University|date=1892|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eXoWAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA128|publisher=Yale University|page=128}}</ref>
==Other versions== Trumbull worked on this painting for many years and created several sketches and final oil paintings. A collection of sketches is located at the [[Princeton University Library]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mellby|first1=Julie L.|title=The Death of General Mercer at the Battle of Princeton|url=https://blogs.princeton.edu/graphicarts/2011/06/the_death_of_mercer_at_the_bat.html|website=Graphic Arts Exhibitions, acquisitions, and other highlights from the Graphic Arts Collection, Princeton University Library}}</ref>
A large scale version ({{convert|72+1/4|in|cm}} x {{convert|108|in|cm}}), painted in 1831, is owned by the [[Wadsworth Atheneum]] in [[Hartford, Connecticut]].<ref name=wadsworth>{{cite web|title=The Death of General Mercer at the Battle of Princeton, January 3, 1777, (painting)|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&menu=search&aspect=Keyword&term=IAP+06910061&index=.NW|work=Inventory of American Sculpture, Smithsonian Institution Research Information System|publisher=[[Smithsonian American Art Museum]]|id=IAP 06910061}} Owner: [[Wadsworth Atheneum]]</ref>
The Yale University Art Gallery also owns an unfinished version dated {{circa|1786}}–{{circa|1788}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artgallery.yale.edu/collections/objects/102|title= The Death of General Mercer at the Battle of Princeton, January 3, 1777 (unfinished version)|publisher=Yale University Art Gallery}}</ref>
